Package org.bluezoo.gumdrop.ftp

Enum FTPAuthenticationResult

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<FTPAuthenticationResult>
      • org.bluezoo.gumdrop.ftp.FTPAuthenticationResult
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<FTPAuthenticationResult>
    public enum FTPAuthenticationResult
extends java.lang.Enum<FTPAuthenticationResult>
    Defines the possible outcomes for FTP authentication attempts. Each result corresponds to specific FTP response codes and indicates how the server should respond to USER/PASS/ACCT command sequences.

    This abstraction allows handler implementations to focus on authentication logic without needing to know FTP protocol response codes.

    Author:
    Chris Burdess

    • Enum Constant Detail

      • SUCCESS

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult SUCCESS
        User is successfully authenticated and logged in (230). The client now has full access based on user permissions.

      • NEED_PASSWORD

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult NEED_PASSWORD
        User name is okay, password is required (331). This is the normal response to a valid USER command.

      • NEED_ACCOUNT

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult NEED_ACCOUNT
        User name is okay, account information is required (332). Some FTP servers require additional account information.

      • INVALID_USER

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult INVALID_USER
        Invalid user name (530). The specified user does not exist or is not allowed to connect.

      • INVALID_PASSWORD

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult INVALID_PASSWORD
        Invalid password (530). The password provided for the user is incorrect.

      • INVALID_ACCOUNT

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult INVALID_ACCOUNT
        Invalid account information (530). The account information provided is incorrect or insufficient.

      • ACCOUNT_DISABLED

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult ACCOUNT_DISABLED
        User account is disabled or locked (530). The user exists but is not currently allowed to log in.

      • TOO_MANY_ATTEMPTS

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult TOO_MANY_ATTEMPTS
        Too many login attempts (421). The client has exceeded the allowed number of authentication attempts.

      • ANONYMOUS_NOT_ALLOWED

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult ANONYMOUS_NOT_ALLOWED
        Anonymous login not allowed (530). The server does not accept anonymous FTP connections.

      • USER_LIMIT_EXCEEDED

        public static final FTPAuthenticationResult USER_LIMIT_EXCEEDED
        Maximum concurrent users exceeded (421). The server has reached its user connection limit.
